The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and published a brochure
Women who are stamped as witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common societal characteristics.
They belong to the older generation, they do not find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If one of these women "becomes" a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate."
"Even young and healthy women are spared this by helping to work and giving birth to children," a nun describes the situation, which in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso takes care of more than one hundred women who have been expelled from their communities.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he published a brochure designed to stop the "witch hunting."
But the thing has a hook.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper "derStandard" pointed out to the dilemma of written enlightenment.
Accused of witchcraft is common in other African countries as well.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men – they poured oil over her and simply lit her on fire.
The incident was reported by the BBC server.
The perpetrators claimed, however, that the matter would have been only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, oil is inflamed, which is used for ritual anointings.
After the group tried to "expel an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports people here regardless of their education.
"The standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Freezers of human souls are as dangerous as they are today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, last year the Gambian president himself got involved.
"President Yahya Jammeh sparked a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt's death, as they allegedly had a share in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic."
"He called on Shamans from nearby Guinea to help, who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the president's bodyguard, violently abducted women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the president's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the incarcerated people were forced to drink an absud from plants with hallucinogenic effect, which also caused bowel and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay on the farm.
