The architects looked in - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything involved: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings originate, calculated from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building with the premises for its company mini-garden.
In wise anticipation, because most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is committed to ensuring that the designers return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the ability to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of its social program.
The construction engineers and architects are thus easier to manage their demanding profession and childcare.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the Arch.Design staff and, with the support of management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidy of CZK 2.8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment were procured and for a period of 2 years qualified personnel and operations were provided.
After the funding has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
The children are taken care of by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, children can attend kindergarten without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, but the day varies over several children.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly tailored to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the corporate hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care, the content of the programme in the mini-kindergarten is still comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What's more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time, eliminating the stress of late picking up the children from a distant kindergarten.
Therefore, parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also formed here.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and strengthen their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi’s interiors
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are torn-down fish moths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splitters and mosaics, the shell-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only when you look closely that you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire facade looks even more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the brightness of the colors.
The same swinging lines and engulfed shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even gull holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gràcia No. 43 was created by the renovation of a house from 1877, carried out by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old and building an entirely new building, but ultimately agreed to Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper renovation.
However, the Casa Batlló rental house was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on his dashboard that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created, and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also contributed to the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house got its organic forms from the local inhabitants due to the nickname "bone house".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "glowing house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system that was unique at the time, with venting ducts and typical fireplaces.
Something strange is already affecting its 45-degree slope.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was not in any way fooled by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded remediation.
Among other things, the councillors also encountered the fact that the building, with its pillars, even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, no changes were made, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request for such a change, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the 3rd floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could conveniently chat without having to renounce a certain intimacy during more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two other floors as a result of Gaudí's renovation of a new facade.
Impressive is Gaudí’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the lighthouses.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum amount of light.
In doing so, he simply made use of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only this year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a rather lucrative business, the visits were kept, indeed they were also extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a stamp, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards receive a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Anyone who wants to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the inhabitants of the house and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed rust? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the bed surface - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
These, however, must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
When choosing, many things play a role - the weight, size, state of health and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior, in which mattress and rust must be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend house that is not heated regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned over regularly.
If they do not have enough vents in the core and are still lying on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is not excluded that it forms under its mold.
Of course, what you are accustomed to also plays a role in the election.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will find it difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Although all the hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can't sleep right here anymore."
"For their shaved shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I recommend these, among other things, to people with diabetes who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can receive the "information" from the joints and skin poorly," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstery furniture.
That’s why I bought these mattresses with visco foam to many ice hockey players years ago, but also to other customers.
"Today, this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by, among others, the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of Visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimises its hardness and shape according to the heat absorbed, in other words, it is directly absorbed by the warm body.
Nowhere does it push, at night you don't roll around like after a hard fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (burn).
When choosing the size of the mattress, one should still take into account the length of the soles of the feet, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Both men and women, who are 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm bed width available, i.e. together 180 cm.
For single beds, for example, singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For comfort and also for potential visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal width of the bed: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the master of the upholstery and room designer, who for years has also focused on the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of this furniture.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own rust and their own mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are equally high.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the grate at different heights and this is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be on the mould layer and the fine padding.
"You should not feel the feathers by hand or by sitting down," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and mattress, like siamese twins, have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses can not be ventilated and the cover can not be washed, which is already going on today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve) after five to seven years.
This is also why professionals reject advertising slogans, which promise a lifetime of up to 25 years, and even a lifetime guarantee for mattresses.
Every thing has its If and But.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of washable, detachable covers, yet it is recommended to use a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although today mattress covers are usually made with a round zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (immeasurably important for the washing process and the size of the washing machine!), manipulation with larger mattresses, especially carried out alone, often has to do with the unequal struggle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a grate?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Also, they should prefer to provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are no already in it) and use mattresses with a spring skeleton and a minimum height of 15 cm with so-called pocket spring cores and fine pads.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong to such a substrate.
For non-adjustable lattice grates with 14 to 18 spring strips (lamels), latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), always pay for grates with a larger number of lattices, i.e. of 28 or more spring strips, with lordose support in the lumbar vertebrae area and the possibility to regulate the lattice hardness.
Adjustable slatted gratings do not include mattresses with a spring skeleton, as they do not react to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which allows the spring strips to be pressed in or even bent so as to allow the shoulder of the sleeper to be punctually lowered.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have begun to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (Lattoflex) or grates with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion suspension are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too big and full) pillow for the right mattress and the right rust, most of the benefits are lost again.
Here too, a rule of thumb: the head cushion should support the head, its tips should only reach to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, therefore, a 50 x 60 cm pillow appears, as the Scandinavians like it, for example.
In the side layer, the head cushion (together with the shoulder relief zone in the rust or the soft zone in the mattress) should compensate for the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former (filled with hay) straw bags.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their mixtures.
Also for mattresses, the new magic word is "bio".
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils such as castor oil and soybean oil are increasingly used to make polyurethane foams.
Soybeans are used by all known manufacturers.
"Organic means mattresses whose core is made of materials of purely natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1>í<0xC4><0x8D>ek of Tropico Plus.
However, natural materials are also used in the manufacture of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also afford microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scents while sleeping.
Again, there is a difference between a man and a woman.
While in men a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves is used so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers have a "warming" effect for women.
Extracts from red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex becomes warm while sleeping.
What about today’s favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and visco foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are located.
However, for a high-quality mattress you have to pay 7000 crowns and more.
Health mattresses, however, are usually charged a lower value added tax, as they are considered medical aids.
As the first Czech company, Gumotex was granted this advantage.
You can see that saving on the mattress and rust is not so easy.
From time to time there are special offers from manufacturers and dealers that offer two mattresses at the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with visco-foam memory for 11,990 CZK.
The second one is available for free.
It was the material Tempur that initiated the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at an almost cosmic pace.
No wonder, they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to huge overloads during the launches.
Tempur becomes soft with heat, in a cool environment it solidifies again.
Thus, it adapts perfectly to the human body and optimally distributes the body pressure.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure fires, but generally increases sleep comfort.
However, viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses, but also for other health products, such as special foot pads, which are intended to provide relief to the legs and vessels.
Local manufacturers use, for example, the foams Eucatherm C, Twinsaver or similar products.
