The Democracy Routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is growing stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These results came from the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly visible in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased significantly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of supporters of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend is also evident in Mexico, where the economy is recovering from last year’s strong economic downturn.
But only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country’s democratic practices, as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Around 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% trust their government. Both values correspond to those of the last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
That this continued even during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were intercepted by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from this week’s UN Economic Commission for Latin America, the rate of poverty in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and dropped again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread forward thinking.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were victims of a crime in the last year, but compared to 38% in the last year, the figures have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in stronger support for the private and market economy: approximately 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private sector is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% said that only the market economy can make progress for their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
According to 19% of respondents (18% last year), Brazil has the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with this role being assumed by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An election slap
No one expected the elections in Haiti on November 28 to be perfect.
But the facts far surpassed the fears of the voters who rushed to help the oppressed country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes, ballot papers in Rinnstein, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were just a part of the problems.
The polling stations opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless as a result of the January earthquake, roamed around in search of a choice.
Some finally gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some alleged top riders, demanded the cancellation of the election results because of an alleged fraud.
There were some violent protests throughout the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, called the election "a pretty good one in many respects".
According to a cautious statement by observers of the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, “these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily render the process invalid.”
In other words, the show goes on.
The election authority, which is allegedly bound by the impopular departing president René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the provisional results on December 7.
The expected election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope for the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former First Lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity lawsuit.
If Jude Célestin, who receives little or no approval from the electorate, declares him the winner of the by-election, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims still live in tents, low voter turnout has been feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to a lack of organization.
Shortly before the election began, about 250,000 passports, which are required for the election, had not yet been distributed.
There's a lot at stake.
The donor countries see a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves are of the same opinion.
Hidden in the middle
In the weeks following the sudden death of her husband, Argentine President Cristina Fernández experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, the highest value since her election in 2007.
However, whether this will help her to be re-elected next year depends on whether the apparently mourning Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who also directed economic policy after his wife’s election, often drafted budget plans that did not fully take tax revenues, economic growth and inflation into account.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra income at their discretion.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided and Kirchner’s death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further defeat.
Some regime critics from the ranks of the ruling peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (in which one parliamentarian punched another in the face and others witnessed the government bribery), Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
"I will not discuss this," the president said.
The 2010 budget now also applies to the next year, giving the President even more opportunity to spend money at her own discretion.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but numerous private estimates - and wage demands from trade unions - drive the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003, when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty eradication as his main goals, not inflation reduction.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector, and cleaned up the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which then beautified the official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
She has called on the private sector and trade union leaders to talks.
And according to official statements, wage increases are expected to be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices of Argentina’s agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
However, inflation undermined the growth momentum by a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to rejoin Argentina financially to the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government reached an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country’s earlier re-indebtedness in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for an agreement with the lenders from the Paris Club, to whom she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as usual elsewhere.
But last month, Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the fund will provide "technical support" in the creation of a new national consumer price index, which seems to be the first step towards cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after the end of her term of office, even without the support of her husband.
If yes, it needs the support of the middle class, which is largely fed up with Churchism.
When the Argentines return from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy that has been brought to them will be shattered.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to cancel many of her husband’s political decisions quietly.
