As the DPP's presidential candidate, Tsai found great approval, like Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything to show that she too is able to build close relations with Beijing.
Tsai is planning a forge of ideas as a point of contact between the DPP and China, but this requires unbiased discussions.
Tsai publicly stated that her party is offering a "trustworthy alternative" to Mas's premature rapprochement with China.
Chen seems very upset about this change.
From his cell, he said the DPP candidates would have done better to insist on Taiwan’s independence.
He even urged pragmatist Su to renounce the presidential nomination.
Even without Chen’s intervention, the DPP finds it difficult to choose its potential candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
Mas values are bad, despite the rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to conduct their election campaign without him.
The main reasons for its unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the ever-increasing scissors between the poor and the rich.
According to a KMT spokesperson, he will redesign his cabinet as well as the local facilities.
The strong presence of the DPP suggests that Taiwan is only in favour of a limited rapprochement.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic cooperation with China as inevitable.
