Arsenic-resistant microbes could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live from arsenic, among others, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the previously considered vital elements.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it something very special, although it's almost a kind of 'foreign' way of life," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears on Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacteria in California’s Mono Lake still grows when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You’re wondering what else is possible,” said co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could deal with the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery “shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can use other elements to initiate biochemical processes and that the ‘standard elements’ that we believe are absolutely vital are not necessarily fixed,” said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton, United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to its chemically similar behavior to that of phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it lubricates almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacteria GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based form of life can naturally occur, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has been no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth ages," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
Other stolen exhibit dogs found in Compton
The remaining two of the four exhibit dogs stolen from a Bellflower motel were found Thursday, according to the Los Angeles County Sheriff.
The four show dogs — two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis — disappeared on Tuesday when unknowns stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van, in which the animals were housed in front of a Bellflower Motel 6 at night, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were discovered on Wednesday afternoon, and the last two on Wednesday evening, explains Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
“The good news is that the dogs are well,” Whitmore said.
“They are in good condition.”
"They were returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore did not give any specific information about the location of the dogs or the circumstances that led to their discovery.
“The investigations are still going on.”
“We don’t want to say that anymore,” Whitmore explains.
"We're tracking some traces."
The dog owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were not available for information on Thursday.
They picked up their two dogs on Wednesday afternoon at a county animal shelter in Downey.
Representatives of the sheriff found the van and the two dogs at different locations in Compton.
The Akitas – Trace, a 3-year-old shepherd, and Didi, a 10-month-old bitch – were unharmed, according to authorities.
But the Corgis Bunny and Peter, who wanted to introduce Rickard and Peek to the competition this week on behalf of their Japanese owners, remained missing until Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were this weekend due to the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach in the city because Trace was supposed to participate in the competition.
As Peek told the Times on Wednesday, the other dogs should take part in other competitions in the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba show.
Southern California is a stop on the couple’s almost one-month tour from dog show to dog show.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked in at the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van in front of their room window.
They took three more dogs - a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell Terrier, and a Brittany - into their motel room.
The thick-skinned Akitas and Corgis stayed in the van because it was cooler there.
They left the window wide open so that the dogs had fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported their car stolen at 6:00 a.m. on Tuesday.
Peek promised anyone who could give a clue to the Corgis a finder's salary, and the animals were implanted with microchips to identify them.
On Thursday, it was not yet known whether a finder's salary would be paid.
The lion roars again after judicial approval of the MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light for a fresh start.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially blessed the “preparing” plan to pay off $5 billion in debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to make new movies and TV shows.
According to Thursday’s statements, the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy law, so the restart of MGM under the leadership of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment, is no longer in the way.
The number of employees is reduced from over 400 to about 320.
For MGM, Chapter 11 does not actually come into effect until JPMorgan Chase has completed a planned $500 million bond to finance the new MGM productions.
At the moment, a consortium of the investment bank, which is itself contributing $75 million, is running the company, with funding expected to be up until mid-December.
The restructuring of the studio began in May 2009 with an order for investment bank Moelis & Co, the management of the company, which struggled with interest payments of $300 million/year, to help solve its financial problems.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO at Enron and restructuring expert who became known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper’s efforts to resolve MGM’s financial concerns and pay off the studio’s more than 140 creditors took longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties decided at the end of 2009 to offer the company for purchase.
However, the auction attracted only a few bidders and no one wanted to pay the $2 billion demanded by the creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything started from scratch when the MGM team began with the restructuring plan, which was finally signed by the creditors at the end of October after months of debates and internal disputes.
If MGM officially survived the bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a multi-million dollar bonus for their work.
The share of Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, is $9.5 million.
Cooper, who was paid $375,000 a month to run the company, receives a $4 million “success bonus.”
Barber and Birnbaum are planning to resume production at MGM. This year, the studio released only one film and created an annual plan with seven or eight films to be released in early 2012.
They are also planning two films after "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio needs a separate bond of $265 million to $275 million for its financial share of the two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who financed approximately 18% of the MGM loan, tried to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, of which he is the largest shareholder.
However, the last negotiations between the two companies did not lead to any results.
