Can politeness connect the separation?
After a campaign of slander and negativity, little politeness has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring about a breakthrough in the big issues that had to be addressed during the so-called "lame duck session", the meeting at the end of a period of government in which no decisions are made.
After all what you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different parties nor a respect for their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partial point-gathering.
The public meeting of the president's deficit committee on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue to exist between the members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that disguises the ideological divide that continues to separate the members from each other.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - one of which calls for a sign of cooperation and compromise from the other, while the same is trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of claims or allegations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health or waiting, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Last but not least, the November election has given Washington a mild vote, at least for a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
In some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have hardly any choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts will end at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of it.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on rising unemployment pay is to be expected, even if only because Republicans can’t afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the White House meeting on Tuesday, the optimism has increased that these issues can be agreed during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratified the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even unavoidable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what happens from today to 2012 as a pre-fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012.
The reasons for this have much to do with the appearance of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their education.
As worried as Republican leaders may be about playing too high, they know they have to try to keep their promises of cutting government spending and repealing health care reform.
These party lines will already become clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Vice Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pushed so much to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation, and they struggle very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little room for flexibility or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama with regard to the state budget, taxes and health care system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partialism and polarization are now larger than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a consequently far wider election in 2012.
In this way, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the issues that still separate the two.
