In a dimly lit, concreted classroom with dirty and bleaching walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminds the man who built it, the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Due to his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule known as "the butcher", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he has built hospitals and bridges, developed the infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing supporters are challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed the victims to engage in public confrontation with the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a school book that for the first time tells children of former soldiers the history of the Khmer Rouge.
And in July, a UN and Cambodia community tribunal sentenced a former member of the Khmer Rouge for the first time when it sentenced the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as the Duke, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear among Khmer Rouge veterans Alnlong Vengs grew, making their efforts for reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodia's society more difficult.
"There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia's Documentation Center, an independent organization that explores the regime.
"For her, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
“It divides families.”
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-Ied government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border to Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla warfare from their base in the west of the mountains and jungle of Cambodia, Ta Mok moved the next generation to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to overwhelm the government, leading to the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not surrendered, was arrested by government forces at the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh Prison, where he awaited his trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the crushing poverty of rural Cambodia and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Although a few Khmer Rouge elite officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the simple soldiers remained poor, unskilled peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling in 1998 to live a life of poor rice growers.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok has given everyone something to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Tribunal has raised concerns here as well.
At the beginning of next year, the court will try Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The task of the court is to condemn the old leaders and those primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will prosecute further acts beyond these four cases.
This has helped little to alleviate the fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in the province of Manteay Meanchey during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials at Cambodia’s Documentation Centre that she had led the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that allegedly killed thousands of forced laborers.
On a hot evening, Im Chaem returned from work on the fields to her wooden house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past with the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to go, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
“If there were no more persecution, there would be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court charged more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But the confrontation with the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center said.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer times means bringing together the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that we can understand everything."
The center created the first government-approved Khmer Rouge textbook, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the High School History Book of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As often in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s connections to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new school book helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he brought the book home to read.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the court," he said.
