Nevertheless, it anticipates a collapse in the interest rate ranges that banks are trying to offset with increases in fees and loan prices.
Sabadell expects to capture one million private customers in three years – an area that still remains to be explored.
Sabadell has found the way to exploit the next three years, thus surviving in a very complicated economic environment.
The Bank will introduce a new three-year framework in 2011.
The aim is not only to survive without using public aid from the FROB, but also to increase the market share by one million private customers - 700,000 if you deduct the customers that the bank will lose - which is the big challenge facing this bank, because until now it has paid more attention to its business customers than it has paid attention to it.
This year, it has added 250,000 private customers and 50,000 companies.
Their market share for retail customers is 3.5 percent, while business customers account for more than 10 percent.
Another principle of the 2011-2013 business plan is the increase in productivity, i.e. austerity, cost reduction. The challenges faced by the bank will present it together with the annual financial report.
Few banks dare to set and publish goals in these difficult times, as the financial crisis has confused all the plans of banks around the world.
This year, Sabadell will complete its Optima Guidance Plan, which was originally designed to last three years, but was extended by one fiscal year due to the market situation.
The customers who leave the savings banks are the main goal of the bank.
At a breakfast organized by the APIE, Guardiola stressed that 2011 would be a “difficult” year “with great reach”.
The manager assumes that Spain would only come out of the crisis "slowly".
In addition, it would be "very difficult" to "create work" in two or three years - fundamental to the survival of banks.
Even if he assumes that the war for liabilities - which penalizes interest rate margins - will fade, the risk surcharges that banks and savings banks will have to pay for their emissions to obtain liquidity will already be rolled down to the price of loans as a compensation for dwindling profit margins.
"The issues of liquidity and financing are structural in nature and they will put pressure on the loans."
"We didn't turn the cock off, but the interest rate differentials are very high," Guardiola admitted.
On Thursday, Banesto issued an order to its branch network to limit the granting of long-term loans and increase the interest rate differentials (cf. Cinco Días of 22 and 27 November).
The manager also admitted that the banks were currently pursuing the strategy of "increasing fees", but "within a framework shaped by competition".
Sabadell’s Lead Plan is based on organic growth, even though the Group, as always, does not exclude corporate business.
It is not in vain that he assures that in Spain "larger companies are needed."
“Everything will change next year,” he said.
He stresses that the need for capital is currently "hugely increasing" and does not preclude some Spanish financial institutions from slipping into red numbers.
He believes that the FROB could replace the money market in the case of capital increases.
After assuring that Sabadell could also survive a temporary closure of the markets, he undermines the argument of some bankers who are already predicting a new liquidity crisis.
He stressed that nothing could be put into circulation, but unlike the incidents in June, short-term financing through repo transactions could be achieved and thus the crisis intercepted.
CECA excludes a second wave of mergers of savings banks
The Director-General of the CECA, José Antonio Olavarrieta, rejected yesterday the possibility of a merger of the savings banks and stressed the speed with which the industry is being restructured.
When the concentration process of the Spanish savings banks began, several savings banks insisted not to participate in the first phase, they reserved the second round.
On the other hand, the Director General of the Spanish Savings Association (CECA), José Antonio Olavarrieta, assured that this second round would not take place.
"I believe that the majority of the mergers have been completed. The inclusion of Cajasol in the Banca Cívica group cannot be considered as a second round, rather it was about adjustments."
"The majority is completed. It may be that we have thirteen or fourteen instead of seventeen, but all the important processes are already completed. They have been controlled by Banco de España, which has strongly supported all the processes."
At a breakfast organised by the Association of Managing Directors and Managers of Aragon (ADEA), Olavarrieta said that the concentration process "was completed as quickly as possible and that we must be satisfied with the timely course that was set in the past, not now, in the framework of business plans with Banco de España", he stressed.
"The transition from 45 savings banks with an average of 28 billion assets to 17 with 75,500 million each is a historically unparalleled process. The number of financial institutions has been reduced by 62 percent and they are now much larger, with which we have complied with the Basel Agreement," he stressed.
Olavarrieta explained that "there would be a number of unanswered opinions about the slowness of the process, which revealed unseriousness and nonsense," because "Banco de España is urging us to conclude on time before the end of the year."
The Director General of the ECSC, José Antonio Olavarrieta, yesterday assured that Spain has one of the most rigorous financing systems in Europe and “perhaps” around the world, adding that those who doubted this would do so “without deeper knowledge”.
The manager noted that in the current economic environment, we do not have to worry about the situation of financial institutions and savings banks, which have undergone a "very significant" concentration process, which will be carried out "as quickly as possible".
He also recalled that the Spanish banks had passed the stress tests carried out by the ECB in July very well.
Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to maintain the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the entire European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has introduced new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and medium-sized enterprises, the regulation of temporary workers or the abolition of the 426 euro support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, as well as the management of the 30 percent of the state airports of Barajas and El Prat.
On the other hand, Deputy Prime Minister Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which clashes with the maintenance of the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark – although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment – is supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reshaping of the euro according to German proposals, which means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the suspension of payments by some countries, as well as the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is unambiguous and has been clear for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the drift between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully delayed the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against saving Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out again with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union agreements to enable the rescue of a country while at the same time obligeing private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it drove the Irish crisis and all that followed.
In the coming months, we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures need to be taken now - from this date the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist.
2013 will be the birth year of a new monetary area, in which the offending countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive external economic balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge gaps in the balance of payments, as it was quoted by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us until the spring of 2013.
Zapatero seems to have understood that, too, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that despite criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like anything would change.
Among the options considered is that we would have to leave the euro area completely blocked by less reputable countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it had warned us.
Sport and circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show a spirit of invention, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being spilled on whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty in the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next phase of the game without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so prevalent that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen about the case presented is that a team of Real Madrid football club (who in his anthem pretended nobility and honor and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who has added one episode more to his long history than the one he has called for.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a circumvention of the rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to be circumventing its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sportsman should be investigated.
The sports mind defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the offending players taking an unjustified advantage from the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand by misrepresentation or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as striking as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders took from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was neither put in a disadvantaged position nor gained advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that the players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, to a certain extent uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also quit. In addition, players with this procedure get a penalty and go into the second card cycle, where they quit with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
So it is not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to maximize the benefits of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a penalty (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they rather wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between invention and rule environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the controversy has arisen as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic in nature.
