Pakistan's nuclear program raises concern in U.S.
Islamabad is manufacturing nuclear weapons "faster than any other country".
WikiLeaks reveals ties between Pakistan and the Taliban.
The content of the correspondence between the North American embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department, revealed by the Internet portal Wikileaks, confirms the enormous concerns posed by the Pakistani nuclear program Washington.
On the fringes of the clarifying and juicy details that the documents on the content of the talks and the thinking of the accredited North American diplomats in Islamabad provide, these reveal that cooperation between the two countries in matters of nuclear security is not strengthened, but on the contrary "decreases" and that the unstable Asian country produces more than one other " atomic land ".
In particular, the peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program – that the weapons are not assembled, but their parts are stored to make their destruction more difficult in the event of a possible attack – prepare Washington for sleepless nights.
In a report before the visit of the former head of the National Security Council, James Jones, the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, cites the following risks: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the area attacked by the Taliban, the presumed dispersion of nuclear material and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear material".
The large number of people implicated in the nuclear arsenals and missile programs is no longer seen by the US alone, but also by Russia as overwhelming and reason to be cautious.
"Pakistan needs to hire strictly credible personnel to monitor its nuclear facilities; because of the low educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work on nuclear or missile programs," Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said in a meeting with his North American counterpart.
New to the documentation revealed by Julian Assange’s Internet portal is that U.S.-Pakistan cooperation on nuclear proliferation is lagging behind and the increased pace at which Pakistan manufactures nuclear weapons.
In May, an embassy office described communication with Pakistan as "frustrating": "Often there is no transparency; we do not receive responses to aid offers or they are rejected."
In another statement, Peter Lavoy, a South Asian state intelligence official, confirmed that “despite the economic disaster, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons as quickly as any other country.”
Ambassador Patterson asks Washington during a visit by the Supreme Leader of the Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to “clearly” to the responsible that “Pakistan’s army must cease its tacit support of terrorist groups.”
In Search of WikiLeaks Chief
Obama appoints a senior anti-terrorism officer to prevent new revelations.
Interpol is issuing a red alert to the pursuit and discovery of Assange.
Everything related to WikiLeaks and its founder, Jullian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth in which the facts are difficult to explain.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a “red alert” to Assange’s “finding and prosecuting.”
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
It’s not new, it’s from November 20th.
It also has nothing to do with the latest disclosure of more than four million U.S. diplomatic documents, but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian must face in Sweden.
WikiLeaks founder’s lawyer, Mark Stephens, said: “The police would know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.”
Already on the 20th, the international police authority based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after receiving the authority by the Swedish authorities.
The 188 Interpol countries are ordered to identify and locate Assange, "to arrest and extradite him provisionally."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many member states, according to the organization, consider the red alert as a free letter of arrest - which must be carried out by the national police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden, where Assange and England.
The move outraged Assange’s lawyers, who yesterday published a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of WikiLeaks is ready to answer questions from the Swedish authorities via videoconferencing.
They also recall that Assange applied for the exit from Sweden and that the prosecutor, who is compared to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s head of security, received the corresponding approval.
"This is like a hunt, not a legal prosecution," the letter said.
As the world searches for him – and his mother from Australia claims her son’s innocence – Assange stays in an unknown place, but not silent.
On Monday, he interviewed the head of Time magazine via Skype from an indefinite location, requesting the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN and thus violate international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign,” he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by the White House press secretary, Robert Gibbs, who described the resignation as “ridden and absurd.”
"I'm not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website," he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a senior anti-terrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent new document disclosures.
President Barack Obama’s attempt to pay less attention to Assange is in contrast to the views of conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House National Security Committee from January, has urged the State Department to investigate the possibility of putting WikiLeaks on the list of terrorist organizations “to seize their funds and prosecute anyone who supports them or makes a contribution.”
Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone even further, and he had to revoke his statement that Assange had to be “assassinated.”
"Obama would have to turn him into a target and use an unmanned plane or something."
Who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and potential presidential candidate.
“Whoever leaked information to the government is guilty of treason, and anything that is not executed is a punishment too mild,” he told Fox.
Puigcercós with a wink to the Carod Immediate Peace in the ERC
The Republican leader allows the party a secret ballot on his continued existence in office.
Huguet proposes a more pluralistic government and the end of the general assembly principle.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe for the tenth time of an internal upheaval in the ranks of the ERC, after losing 11 MPs and half of the electorate vote.
The party leader is aware that his resignation threat is not enough for former party leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that the influence of this sector is as weak today as her mentor himself and will not give him the same headaches as other former leaders.
That is why the leader of Esquerra tries to win the new critics with a wink, which would secure his position until the next municipal elections.
To begin with, yesterday he announced that the more than 200 regional council members of ERC could speak secretly about his stay in office.
With ballot papers, not with a raised hand.
If the carodists wanted to miss a penalty for the president, they could do so without fearing retaliation.
In fact, the boss wants to avoid both the impression of division and that of submission to his person.
In several interviews he reaffirmed that he would feel unconfirmed with half of the votes plus one, and he added without specifying percentage values, a result "in the Bulgarian style" would not be good either.
The Carods demand more from the president than just the party to provide his office, an inadequate gesture since Puigcercós controls the supreme organ of congress.
But since they do not have a sufficient majority to enforce resignations, they will agree with the board on an action plan from now to May.
To this end, they expect to be able to contribute to the drafting of the document on strategic reorientation, which the management will submit to the Council for a vote on the 18th.
In return, Puigcercós promises to postpone the congress in the fall of 2011, which the party leadership already believes to be a fact.
The party chairman of the ERC believes that “polyphony” is detrimental to stability and he strives once and for all to enable the organization to wash its dirty laundry behind closed doors.
In this sense, the article signed by incumbent Councillor Josep Huguet in his blog is symptomatic.
Given that Puigcercós is an ideologist, the owner of Innovació considered it a fact that the party chairman was being supported "in exchange for different goals".
He counted five, two of which are in the foreground.
First, the "restructure" of the board so that it represents at least 90 percent of the party members, that is, the inclusion of new faces from Carod's environment.
The second could be the big news.
Huguet suggests that ERC should finally give up the general assembly principle as a way of functioning.
In doing so, he advocates a reform of the statutes, which will allow congresses to be held with elected delegates.
Puigcercós's team, who fought for the last two congresses, is obsessed with the end of the general assembly model - an exception in the Spanish party system.
In fact, at the 2008 shaking assembly, the party leadership was tasked with reviewing the principle of the plenary assembly at a congress to deal with the reform of the statutes.
This date is still awaited, as infogle of the internal upheaval of the last years was not advisable to address this matter.
Now, without the critical sectors on the horizon, the time might have come to take up this matter again and complete it forever.
