China maintains its targets to reduce greenhouse gases
At COP16, China said it had made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, says Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said that in the last four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, state authorities had worked with those of the central state and municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he said, several multi-year plans have already been initiated or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which was introduced in the last five years and which had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and private hands.
There is also a project at the provincial level on climate change, another on the exchange of traditional bulbs through energy-saving bulbs and another on the weakening and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, the country’s scientific adviser to the government on climate change, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than commonly accepted.
He showed that the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amount to six tons per person, while in the United States there are 100 tons. China is responsible for a total contribution of nine percent to environmental pollution.
There is also unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has been increased by twenty percent in the last five years and another is expected to happen by 2020, he explained.
