The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves for visa application before their interview with the consulate at the service points; costs will be shortened waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa change at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves before their interview at the consulate at the service offices for visa application (ASC, the initial letters in English).
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost for the processing of the visa decreases, as it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out separately.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers), and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only need to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate stay there less time than before.
Those applying for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
