Dupont partly corrected
Quebec broadcaster Stéphane Dupont has suffered a partial setback before the Canadian Broadcasting Standards Supervisory Board (CCNR) due to his controversial statements on social welfare and Haitians as well as his delayed speeches on radio.
The CCNR is of the opinion that Mr Dupont and his CHOI 98.1 FM team have the right to express their own opinions, but that certain statements have "inaccurate information about social welfare and unjustified negative representations of Haitians, as well as such unbridled speeches about the daily broadcast."
The Supervisory Board also concluded that a discussion on suicide, which involves the dissemination of the names of two persons who committed suicide, violates the Radio Broadcasting Code.
The CCNR had received several complaints concerning the comments made during the broadcasts in 2008 and 2010.
The first order was filed following a complaint from the "Front commun des personnes assistées sociales du Québec".
The activist organization had complained that the amounts mentioned in the broadcast were inaccurate.
The moderators should provide more solid than misleading information.
On the subject of suicide, moderator Stéphane Dupont had argued that suicide was an expression of cowardice.
The majority of supervisory board members had concluded that the message conveyed here was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life crises.
"The majority of the Supervisory Board considers that the questionable consequences of the Dupont le midi broadcast would have addressed a sensitive issue in a family-friendly and appropriate manner."
Therefore, he was not charged with any guilt towards his person.
The last point of contention was the statements related to the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had delivered a media-intensive controversy in this regard, which has provoked a lot of reactions.
The CHOI moderator had stated that he had not donated to Haiti aid, since it was not certain whether the needy would actually receive the donations.
The Supervisory Board is of the opinion that these comments were not of an abusive nature, but that their cumulative effect presents an unwarranted negative representation of Haitians.
"I have already served my three-day suspension in this case."
"My file has been virginal for a year and a half," the moderator said.
In all decisions, the Supervisory Board denounces the dissemination of an unbridled form of expression.
In all cases, the CHOI-FM broadcaster has acted "beyond his obligations".
The consequences for the broadcaster, which, inter alia, should have communicated its decisions once during the main broadcasting period within a period of three days, are minor.
