450 million in contracts without tender
Hydro-Québec has agreed to grant project planning companies $450 million in contracts for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydropower project.
In the middle of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts is a consortium consisting of the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which received the most important share, namely that of the project management, for a total of $295 million without a tender.
This consortium, called "Énergie gérance", was formed in 2004 as a companion to the decision of Hydro-Québec, the private sector, to transfer its responsibility for this important hydroelectric project in the amount of $5 billion.
At the beginning of 2005, the consortium "Énergie gérance" drafted the lucrative contract without a public tender.
For the Parti Québécois, resorting to corporate consortia poses a serious ethical problem, which raises the risk of distortion of competition as well as price increases.
"This is a new way of playing a mapped game and it weakens the competition."
"This means that games are now being played in an open form rather than in a secret way," Sylvain Simard, a member of the PQ, told a news conference.
In the early morning, Simard had raised the question before the National Assembly, because it seems to him difficult to understand how the interest of the public can be served in this way.
Minister of Resources Nathalie Normandeau had reacted to this in the afternoon by vehemently declaring that this contract had been a mapped game.
"I remain faithful to my line," she said, reaffirming that the PQ had been "unreasonable" and "lack of hardness".
She said it was "the least" that the PQ apologized.
The model of the consortium is a worldwide practice.
It is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to bundle their expertise in a bid to a tender for a complex project.
The project "Eastmain" has a high level of complexity in terms of its scope of work.
The construction process is underway and is expected to be completed by 2012.
Nevertheless, the contract was awarded without any competition having been able to take place; there had already been negotiations.
Moreover, the model of the consortium in Quebec is no longer an exception even for relatively simple projects.
As the newspaper "Le Devoir" noted last week, the consortium's model applied in the field of civil engineering and consulting is the subject of government investigations.
A short overflight of the Quebec Business Register allows to name more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be of lasting duration.
In this way, for example, Dessau works in partnership with the majority of its core competitors, which include CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin or also Roche and Tecsult.
Any association, and there are several dozen of them, leads back to the same legal entity, namely Dessau.
With regard to the consortium "Energie gérance", Minister Normandeau stressed that "the territory of the Baie James is subject to a particular labour force dynamic and that Hydro-Québec has taken this fact into account in a special way since the 1970s".
Réal Laporte, the great employer of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has made a statement that has turned a blind eye to the fact that the contract for project management was approved after agreement.
"If you bid and there are only a few applicants, your prizes will go up."
"So you have two options: either you take the people who are on this Mart and you say, 'We're going to negotiate a satisfactory deal at a good price.'"
"The idea, however, is that it is not the price that is decisive, but the expertise of the people," Laporte reaffirmed.
This contract approved by the Energy Gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than 50,000 dollars received from the Parti Québécois.
The contracts were approved by either Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
According to the review, the newspaper "Le Devoir" included more than 100 engineering and consulting contracts, which were approved by companies or their branches, including in particular resource laboratories, between 2002 and March 2010.
SNC-Lavalin had acquired 22 contracts, Genivar had received 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account their participation in "Energie gérance".
All these contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the contract with "Energy gérance" over $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard had stated that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) of the "Parti libéral du Québec are well known".
Minister Normandeau had accused the PQ of being equally linked to the companies they “financed” before she clarified that they were rather their executives.
