Global Plan for Renewing Lighting
The United Nations today proposed in Cancun a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction, which corresponds to nearly a third of the additional reduction that must be realized to stabilize the Earth’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of compelling reduction commitments from industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of the FCKWs released to the earth due to lighting would be avoided if the white glowing bulbs, which so far represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better still, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the global vehicle fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans that would reduce global HFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would still have to be deducted from this balance to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from now until 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is again reduced by twice.
Compact fluorescent bulbs average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - by the way, this company has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-lit bulb, which is an indication of the savings possibilities of the exchange plan in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that iese completely new types of bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a rule resistor.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the producers provide a reception point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report outlines in detail the gains that any country would make thanks to this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
