Unemployment rate in France remained stable in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Office (IAA), the unemployment rate in France is stable at 9.3% in the metropolis (including the overseas departments at 9.7%), according to provisional, seasonally adjusted data published on Thursday by the Federal Statistical Office Insee.
The unemployment figure in the metropolis is established at 2,631 million.
The figures for the second quarter were 9.3% of the working population in the metropolis and 9.7% involving the overseas departments.
Over the year, the unemployment rate increased by 0.1 percentage points.
In more detail, 3.4 million workers in the French metropolis were unemployed in the third quarter, but wanted to find a job, including whether or not they were able to work every two weeks or whether or not they were looking for work.
The situation of young people in the labour market has continued to deteriorate with an increase in the unemployment rate of 24.2% in the metropolis (+0.9 percentage points within three months, +0.5 percentage points over the year) and 25% involving the overseas regions.
In the third quarter, 637,000 of the 15- to 24-year-olds were unemployed, according to the IAA.
Seniors, for their part, have seen a slight increase in the unemployment rate of 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 percentage points seen over three months and over the year), i.e. 482,000 people over the age of 50, 6.6% involving the overseas departments.
Only the 25-49-year-olds were able to benefit from the stability of unemployment in the third quarter; 8.3% in the metropolis (-0.1 percentage point over three months, +0.1 percentage points over a year) and 8.8% in France as a whole.
After a discussion about its calculation procedures, the Federal Statistical Office Insee has no longer published the monthly unemployment figures since 2006.
On the other hand, Eurostat, the statistical office of the European Union, continues in this method, announcing on Tuesday a quota of 9.8% in France for October (including the overseas departments) compared with 9.9% in September.
