In fact, he had done nothing in this regard.
A diplomatic telegram edited in Paris on 12 August 2009 is entitled "Iran: French Comments on the Way of Handling Hostage Takings".
François Richier, Elysée consultant on strategy issues, spoke with American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone, accompanied by Patrice Paoli, director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East.
They explained to her the French method.
They advised the Americans to make every effort to bring back their own nationals who would be held forcibly in Iran.
"Make noise," they said, "articulates loudly and clearly and without omission" the words "fundamental human rights", "innocence", "immediate release" in the media.
This is necessary to embarrass the Iranian regime, which is very sensitive to its image.
"Do this all the more, especially since the Iranians are asking you not to do it."
Because "silence solves nothing", past the attempts to discuss indiscriminately, the Iranians are "masters in evasive maneuvers".
Mr Richier adds that the arrest of foreigners is a "common Iranian tactic": "the taking of hostages for the purpose of political blackmail".
He announces the release of Clotilde Reiss from prison (which should take place on August 16, the day she flees to the French embassy) "demands the payment of a large sum of money to the Iranians" (230,000 euro bail).
And he makes it clear that the Elysée anticipates further hostage-taking, a phenomenon that will "intensify itself".
The Iranians could “in the near future arrest another of the approximately 1,800 French citizens living in Iran,” he said.
