Climate: How France Speaks Beautifully of its Financial Promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the swiftly-resolved financing promises (also called "fast start" or "early funding") made by developing countries.
And already the coarse French beauty shops have been uncovered.
Under the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years, while France has pledged 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU pulled all the registers to convince its partners of the fact of their commitment to fast-start funding: detailed progress report from their Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its real value: developing countries and civil society would love to see all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, which puts it on the right path to respecting its commitment of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But if you look into the details, things are a bit more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional commitment has been made without going to the detriment of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the right value they consider best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen itself as a benchmark for 2009: international funding will be retained, and will provide 150 million for three years of "fast start" funding.
Other countries have chosen similar guideline values, either for the year or for conditions at the level of public development assistance.
In return, France considered the funding of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there are no indicative figures for expenditure in the previous year or at the global level of public development aid.
Specifically, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or also decrease) - France claims to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" funding.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, are 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed as equivalent to 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emission mitigation projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro, which is taken as the equivalent of a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan should be taken as the equivalent of the capital.
But France has nothing other in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking up 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are fulfilling their commitments 100% with donations.
In other words, if the overwhelming majority of the European Union spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfil its obligations, France is only giving 10 cents and understands a similar commitment.
Nice hokuspokus!
