Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child consumes 81 different chemicals over the course of a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "in view of the small number of samples analyzed do not represent a statistically significant value, but represent an illustrative character of the problem treated," had between July and September the food usually consumed within four, from a roughly ten-year-old child to the meals plus a meal in Paris and a meal in the super meal.
These typical meals—including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit portions, three dairy products, and 1.5 liters of water per day—were investigated as well as nasheries by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and other pollutants.
The plate balance is depressing: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruption factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if in the approximate totality of cases the legal limits for each chemical, individually ingested substance are not exceeded, it is very well inferred from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrinine inclusion is exposed to the disturbing factor", the authors conclude.
Already at breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three that have been proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, for which the study found traces of a strictly banned insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the steak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemicals were spiked.
In the tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was the "most abundant", and even the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not unburdened.
The ultimate risk of this “polluting cocktail” to the consumer “is likely to be underestimated,” the study said.
For its part, the Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the "growing of civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables that are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
